Bug: T308475
Change-Id: I0ce263bc0ad8f8e6b3f6c6543de92b4a0a6feea9

mediawiki.util: Make internal repeatString() function non-public

Follows-up 63a952c. This function wasn't meant to be a public API
and is not likely to last on its own given no external use case,
easy to locally own where needed, and a built-in exists in ES6. In
order to avoid making this difficult to remove later on, keep it
private.

Also:
- remove branch for now-impossible Infinity condition.
- remove condition for impossible empty string,
  the loop achieves the same if this failure scenario were to happen
  by accident in the future.
- remove condition for impossible negative count,
  if a future accident causes this to be possible, it will now fail
  by effectively assuming count=0 via the loop whereas previously
  it effectively assumed count=1 by returning str as-is.
- further localise var declarations where possible per current code
  conventions.

pull_request.title: Project maintenance updates
pull_request.body:
**Phabricator:** 
https://phabricator.wikimedia.org/T308500

### Notes
These are various version update changes. Some are specifically for Xcode 13.3.1, and some are just general maintenance.

1. Updated .xcversion and config.yml to choose the latest Xcode and iOS simulators for the build server and CircleCI.
2. A couple of changes to targets on recent new files to get things compiling properly.
3. Added automatic Package.resolved change that Xcode 13.3.1 generated for me.
4. Ran `bundle update` to update fastlane
5. Cocoalumberjack had warnings in Xcode, so I set it to the latest version to remove them.

### Test Steps
1. Be sure CircleCI tests pass
2. Be sure project runs in simulator and on device in Xcode 13.3.1. Comment with any warnings you see.

FYI, with each commit I have been kicking off an Experimental build on Jenkins, so deployment is already tested.

review.body: Working well on my local install of Xcode 13.3.1 and CircleCI

service::docker: refresh the service when its image is updated

Puppet currently only triggers a pull of the image if it does not exist
locally. However, to support services running at `latest`, we have to
query the image registry to make sure that the local version of the
image is not stale.

Unfortunately there is no idempotent way to make this check using the
CLI. docker-pull does not have a --dry-run mode (feature request:
https://github.com/distribution/distribution/issues/2412), nor is there
another straightforward way to use the docker CLI to check if an image
is up-to-date. It's possible to query the registry via curl, but it's
not pretty : https://stackoverflow.com/a/64309017/582542 .

The solution I landed on (in which the 'unless' clause actually updates
the image, and the main exec is a dummy) is a bit ugly but it works.

P:openstack: make pdns-recusor listen on ipv6

The ns-recusor dns records have IPv6 addresses listed, so this commit
makes the cloudservices hosts listen on that address for DNS records.

This likely won't have any practical effects since our clients don't
have IPv6 connectivity, but it just feels the right thing to do.
